            <fr:title text="Rules for NK">Rules for NK</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>NK has all the <fr:link href="/lectures/0078/" title="Rules in NJ" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/0078/" display-uri="0078" type="local">rules in NJ</fr:link>, plus:</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>4</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>15</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/007H/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>007H</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/007H/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="LEM:">LEM:</fr:title>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
                  <fr:resource hash="e8866093b9a6a2000f895a55566dbd0a">
                    <fr:resource-content>
                      <html:img src="/lectures/e8866093b9a6a2000f895a55566dbd0a.svg" />
                    </fr:resource-content>
                    <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[
  \usepackage {bussproofs}
  \newcommand {\DP }{\DisplayProof }
  ]]></fr:resource-source>
                    <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[
        \AxiomC{\ensuremath{\vphantom{|}}}
        \LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  LEM:\quad }}
        \UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{A \lor  \neg  A\vphantom{|}}}
        \DP
        ]]></fr:resource-source>
                  </fr:resource>
                </html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
              <fr:month>4</fr:month>
              <fr:day>15</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/0075/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>0075</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/lectures/0075/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Two variations">Two variations</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>    Finally, I'll close by telling you about two simple variations on this proof system.
    NJ itself will form the main proof system we look at, but it'll be handy to know about these two variations as well.
</html:p>
            <html:p>    The first variation is called NM.
    It's very simple: it's exactly the same as NJ, except that it doesn't include the rule <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bot  E]]></fr:tex>.
    The connective <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bot ]]></fr:tex> is still present in the language.
    In NM, this connective has no rules of any sort associated with it.
    Everything else is just the same as in NJ.
    So any proof you make in NJ, if it happens not to use the rule <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bot  E]]></fr:tex>, is also a proof in NM.
    And every proof in NM is itself a proof in NJ directly.
</html:p>
            <html:p>    The second variation is called NK.
    Instead of taking away from NJ, as NM does, the system NK adds to it.
    In particular, NK includes every rule of NJ, plus also the following rule:</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>4</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>15</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/007H/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>007H</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/007H/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="LEM:">LEM:</fr:title>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
                  <fr:resource hash="e8866093b9a6a2000f895a55566dbd0a">
                    <fr:resource-content>
                      <html:img src="/lectures/e8866093b9a6a2000f895a55566dbd0a.svg" />
                    </fr:resource-content>
                    <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[
  \usepackage {bussproofs}
  \newcommand {\DP }{\DisplayProof }
  ]]></fr:resource-source>
                    <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[
        \AxiomC{\ensuremath{\vphantom{|}}}
        \LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  LEM:\quad }}
        \UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{A \lor  \neg  A\vphantom{|}}}
        \DP
        ]]></fr:resource-source>
                  </fr:resource>
                </html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>
    This rule is called "LEM" for the Law of Excluded Middle.
    It allows us to prove any sentence of the form <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \lor  \neg  A]]></fr:tex>, out of nowhere, anywhere we like in a proof.
    It's kind of like a specialized rule of assumption, except that it does not involve any open assumptions.
    It counts as an outright proof of such sentences; like <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\top  I]]></fr:tex>, it creates a new proof from nothing.
</html:p>
            <html:p>    For example, here is a proof in NK that is not also a proof in NJ:
</html:p>
            <html:p>
              <fr:resource hash="a0459f0025727fd766f6f7e28b37288e">
                <fr:resource-content>
                  <html:img src="/lectures/a0459f0025727fd766f6f7e28b37288e.svg" />
                </fr:resource-content>
                <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[
  \usepackage {bussproofs}
  \newcommand {\DP }{\DisplayProof }
  ]]></fr:resource-source>
                <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[
            \AxiomC{\ensuremath{\vphantom{|}}}
        \LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  LEM:\quad }}
        \UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{q \lor  \neg  q\vphantom{|}}}
                \AxiomC{\ensuremath{\vphantom{|}}}
            \LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  LEM:\quad }}
            \UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{p \lor  \neg  p\vphantom{|}}}
                    \AxiomC{\ensuremath{(p \land  q) \rightarrow  r\vphantom{|}}}
                        \AxiomC{\ensuremath{[p]^2\vphantom{|}}}
                        \AxiomC{\ensuremath{[q]^5\vphantom{|}}}
                    \LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \land  I:\quad }}
                    \BinaryInfC{\ensuremath{p \land  q\vphantom{|}}}
                \LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \rightarrow  E:\quad }}
                \BinaryInfC{\ensuremath{r\vphantom{|}}}
            \LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \rightarrow  I^3:\quad }}
            \UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{p \rightarrow  r\vphantom{|}}}
                \AxiomC{\ensuremath{[\neg  p]^2\vphantom{|}}}
                \AxiomC{\ensuremath{[p]^1\vphantom{|}}}
            \LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \neg  E:\quad }}
            \BinaryInfC{\ensuremath{\bot \vphantom{|}}}
            \LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \bot  E:\quad }}
            \UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{r\vphantom{|}}}
            \LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \rightarrow  I^1:\quad }}
            \UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{p \rightarrow  r\vphantom{|}}}
            \LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \lor  E^2:\quad }}
            \TrinaryInfC{\ensuremath{p \rightarrow  r\vphantom{|}}}
        \LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \lor  I_l:\quad }}
        \UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{(p \rightarrow  r) \lor  (q \rightarrow  r)\vphantom{|}}}
            \AxiomC{\ensuremath{[\neg  q]^5\vphantom{|}}}
            \AxiomC{\ensuremath{[q]^4\vphantom{|}}}
            \LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \neg  E:\quad }}
            \BinaryInfC{\ensuremath{\bot \vphantom{|}}}
            \LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \bot  E:\quad }}
            \UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{r\vphantom{|}}}
            \LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \rightarrow  I^4:\quad }}
            \UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{q \rightarrow  r\vphantom{|}}}
        \LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \lor  I_r:\quad }}
        \UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{(p \rightarrow  r) \lor  (q \rightarrow  r)\vphantom{|}}}
        \LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \lor  E^5:\quad }}
        \TrinaryInfC{\ensuremath{(p \rightarrow  r) \lor  (q \rightarrow  r)\vphantom{|}}}
        \DP]]></fr:resource-source>
              </fr:resource>
            </html:p>
            <html:p>        This is a proof of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(p \rightarrow  r) \lor  (q \rightarrow  r)]]></fr:tex>, with the sole open assumption <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(p \land  q) \rightarrow  r]]></fr:tex>.
    We'll think next time about the relation between proof systems and logics.
    It will emerge there that NJ, NM, and NK all determine different logics from each other.
    Two of these logics are new to us: NJ determines a logic called "intuitionistic logic", and NM one called "minimal logic".
    But NK determines a logic we've already met in our earlier lectures.
    More on this next time!</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
